\begin_layout Problem
Verify
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle p\rangle=\hbar k,\hspace{1em}\langle p^{2}\rangle=\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2d^{2}}+\hbar^{2}k^{2},\label{eq:ExpectationPP2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for the expectation value of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}$
\end_inset

 from the Gaussian wave packet given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle=\left[\frac{1}{\pi^{1/4}\sqrt{d}}\right]\exp\left[ikx^{\prime}-\frac{x^{\prime2}}{2d^{2}}\right].\label{eq:GaussianPackage}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
First let's say something about the problem: for this part we have to prove
 that the expectation value for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ExpectationPP2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and for doing so we have to use the Gaussian package given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GaussianPackage"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 which is written in the position basis.
 Now let's move to the calculations: we're going to make use of the following
 relationships, which we know are valid for this wave function in particular
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle x\rangle=0,\hspace{1em}\langle x^{2}\rangle=\frac{d^{2}}{2},
\]

\end_inset

on the other hand, we also know that the momentum operator represented in
 the position basis is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\rightarrow-i\hbar\partial_{x}.
\]

\end_inset

Now, by definition we have that for any operator 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, it's expectation value, calculated in the position basis, is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle f(x)\rangle=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx^{\prime}\langle\alpha|x^{\prime}\rangle f(x^{\prime})\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

and for this particular case, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle p\rangle=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx^{\prime}\langle\alpha|x^{\prime}\rangle p\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

but we know the representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in this basis, thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle p\rangle=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx^{\prime}\langle\alpha|x^{\prime}\rangle\left(-i\hbar\partial_{x^{\prime}}\right)\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

and for a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

better presentation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, I'm going to calculate the derivative on its own, and later plug it in
 the integral, and while doing so, I'm going to do the folowing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

change of variables
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{\prime}\rightarrow x,\hspace{1em}\beta=\frac{1}{\pi^{1/4}\sqrt{d}},
\]

\end_inset

and with this, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i\hbar\partial_{x^{\prime}}\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle\rightarrow i\hbar\partial_{x}\langle x|\alpha\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i\hbar\partial_{x}\langle x|\alpha\rangle=i\hbar\partial_{x}\left(\beta\exp\left[ikx-\frac{x^{2}}{2d^{2}}\right]\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies i\hbar\partial_{x}\langle x|\alpha\rangle=i\hbar\beta\exp\left[ikx-\frac{x^{2}}{2d^{2}}\right]\partial_{x}\left(ikx-\frac{x^{2}}{2d^{2}}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies i\hbar\partial_{x}\langle x|\alpha\rangle=i\hbar\beta\exp\left[ikx-\frac{x^{2}}{2d^{2}}\right]\left(ik-\frac{x}{d^{2}}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies i\hbar\partial_{x}\langle x|\alpha\rangle=i^{2}\hbar k\beta\exp\left[ikx-\frac{x^{2}}{2d^{2}}\right]-\frac{i\hbar\beta}{d^{2}}x\exp\left[ikx-\frac{x^{2}}{2d^{2}}\right],
\]

\end_inset

but using the definition given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GaussianPackage"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the previous equation can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i\hbar\partial_{x}\langle x|\alpha\rangle=i^{2}\hbar k\langle x|\alpha\rangle-\frac{i\hbar}{d^{2}}x\langle x|\alpha\rangle,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies-i\hbar\partial_{x}\langle x|\alpha\rangle=-i^{2}\hbar k\langle x|\alpha\rangle+\frac{i\hbar}{d^{2}}x\langle x|\alpha\rangle=\left(-i^{2}\hbar k+\frac{i\hbar}{d^{2}}x\right)\langle x|\alpha\rangle,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\therefore-i\hbar\partial_{x}\langle x|\alpha\rangle=\left(-i^{2}\hbar k+\frac{i\hbar}{d^{2}}x\right)\langle x|\alpha\rangle\label{eq:PWave}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and if we insert the previous equation into the expectation equation for
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle p\rangle=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx^{\prime}\langle\alpha|x^{\prime}\rangle\left(-i\hbar\partial_{x^{\prime}}\right)\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx^{\prime}\langle\alpha|x^{\prime}\rangle\left(-i^{2}\hbar k+\frac{i\hbar}{d^{2}}x^{\prime}\right)\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\langle p\rangle=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx^{\prime}\langle\alpha|x^{\prime}\rangle\left(-i^{2}\hbar k+\frac{i\hbar}{d^{2}}x^{\prime}\right)\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\langle p\rangle=-i^{2}\hbar k\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx^{\prime}\langle\alpha|x^{\prime}\rangle\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle+\frac{i\hbar}{d^{2}}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx^{\prime}\langle\alpha|x^{\prime}\rangle x^{\prime}\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle p\rangle=-i^{2}\hbar k\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx^{\prime}\langle\alpha|x^{\prime}\rangle\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle+\frac{i\hbar}{d^{2}}\langle x\rangle
\]

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx^{\prime}\langle\alpha|x^{\prime}\rangle\langle x^{\prime}|\alpha\rangle=1,\hspace{1em}\langle x\rangle=0,
\]

\end_inset

because the eigenfunctions are normalized, and the expectation value of
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for this wave function in the position basis is zero, ad then we have that
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle p\rangle=-i^{2}\hbar k+\frac{i\hbar}{d^{2}}\left(0\right),
\]

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{2}=1$
\end_inset

, then we end with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle p\rangle=\hbar k,
\]

\end_inset

just as we wanted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Now, let's move to the second part, in this we have to calculate the expectation
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}$
\end_inset

, then, using the same procedure.
 Again, we know that the momentum representation in this basis is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $p\rightarrow-i\hbar\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p^{2}\rightarrow\left(-i\hbar\right)^{2}\partial_{x}^{2},
\]

